  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Title 18 U.S. Code Section 1956 (Laundering of Monetary Instruments)\n- Title 18 U.S. Code Section 1957 (Engaging in Monetary Transactions in Property Derived from Specified Unlawful Activity)\n\n2. State-Level Statutes:\n- Many states have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws\n\n3. International Cooperation:\n- The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) provides global standards and recommendations for combating money laundering\n\nThese statutes typically:\n- Define money laundering\n- Establish criminal penalties\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Mandate record-keeping and reporting requirements\n- Provide mechanisms for asset forfeiture\n\nThe primary goals of these statutes are to:\n- Prevent criminals from concealing the origins of illegally obtained money\n- Disrupt criminal financial networks\n- Promote financial transparency\n- Protect the integrity of financial systems\n\nPenalties can include significant fines and imprisonment for individuals and organizations found guilty of money laundering.",
